column3: Opening Day at the Polo Grounds saw much ceremony as NY's 1924 pennant was hoisted, and tribute was paid to the Eddie Grant Memorial, with Hughie Jennings and Dave Bancroft laying the wreath, and the crowd giving a minute of silence Supreme Court Justice Robert F. Wagner threw out first pitchFILENAME_TX"

Youngs, Ump O'Day, and Smith jockeyed about the plate after Youngs had taken two balls.  Pep stepped out of the box when Aldridge hesitated on the mound.  Then O'Day stepped out and began to dust off the plate.  Smith also moved out to make it unanimous.1925NY1.EVN.regular.comment.csv"

With a 2-2 count on Kelly, Aldridge and Smith had a conference.  Aldridge then tried to break a curve over the outside corner that Ump O'Day called a ball.  Aldridge and Smith were vigorous in their protests; Smith had quite a rumpus with O'Day; Kelly drove the next pitch into the LF stands about 10 feet foul.  He then was called out on a fine curve.  There were many cheers for Aldridge.1925NY1.EVN.regular.comment.csv"
